The generated override uses a nullable value type, which doesn't compile:

```c#
public override int? M()
{
    throw new NotImplementedException();
}
```

There is an existing bug in CoreCLR (not mono or CoreRT) where the following legal code throws a type load exception:

```csharp
static class Program
{
    static void Main()
    {
        var m = new M();
    }
}

struct N<T> { }
struct M { public N<M> E; }
```

The bug is unlikely to be fixed any time soon. See discussion starting at https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/issues/6924#issuecomment-547078135.

I think this would be a good candidate for a warning wave so people don't accidentally write code, which whilst legal, won't actually run in the most popular runtime.

**Version Used**: 
Visual C# Compiler Version 3.7.0-6.20459.4 (7ee7c540)

**Steps to Reproduce**:
Use code below and create `SurveyQuestion` class.

```
    #nullable enable
    public class SurveyQuestion
    {
        public string QuestionText { get; }

        public SurveyQuestion()
        {
            QuestionText.ToString();
            QuestionText = "";
        }
    }
```

**Expected Behavior**:
Warning for possible null dereference of `QuestionText` for calling `ToString`. In TooltipText in Visual Studio should be show that it is null!
**Actual Behavior**:
No warning at compile time. In TooltipText in Visual Studio shows that it is not null!

